ild within this complex historical conjuncture of a nation looking back on decades of authoritarian rule and forward to an uncertain future. Examining films from several genres by four key directors of the Transition – Carlos Saura, Antonio Mercero, Víctor Erice, and Jaime de Armiñán – Inhabiting the In-Between explores how the child is represented as both subject and object, self and other, and consistently cast in a position between categories or binary poles. Its readings demonstrate how the cinematic child that materializes in this period is a fundamentally shifting, oscillating, ambivalent figure that points toward the impossibility of fully comprehending the historical past and the figure of the other, while inviting an ethical engagement with each.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChildren in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictureszSpainxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  aFranco dictatorship.  aGeneral Francisco Franco.  aSpanish Transition to Democracy.  achildhood.  acinema.  acontemporary Spain.  afilm in Spain.  ahistory of Spanish film.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753108940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487531089423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487531089.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles